  "format": "Sean and Amanda see 'Tenet' at a San Diego drive-in and try to recount its plot, after working through the Academy's new Best Picture rules and a fall theatrical slate coming apart at the seams. Plus: Antonio Campos on 'The Devil All the Time'.",
  "segments": [
    {
      "kind": "discussion",
      "heading": "Festivals are back, and so is the acquisition market",
      "note": "the virtual TIFF / Telluride weekend",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Nomadland",
          "year": 2020,
          "note": "Won the Golden Lion at Venice; seen at a Telluride drive-in and, for Sean, one of the year's best."
        },
        {
          "title": "Pieces of a Woman",
          "year": 2020,
          "note": "Vanessa Kirby and Shia LaBeouf; picked up by Netflix, which already holds the deepest Oscar slate."
        },
        {
          "title": "Bruised",
          "year": 2021,
          "note": "Halle Berry's directorial debut, as an aging MMA fighter; another Netflix buy."
        },
        {
          "title": "Malcolm & Marie",
          "year": 2021,
          "note": "Written and directed by Sam Levinson during quarantine; Netflix reportedly paid $30M for the John David Washington / Zendaya two-hander."
        },
        {
          "title": "Joe Bell",
          "year": 2021,
          "note": "Mark Wahlberg drama still without a distributor at festival time; Sean expects it to sell fast."
        },
        {
          "title": "One Night in Miami",
          "year": 2020,
          "note": "Regina King's directorial debut, bought earlier in the month by Amazon; a likely Oscar contender."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "discussion",
      "heading": "The Academy's new Best Picture standards",
      "note": "two of four, mostly below the line",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "The Irishman",
          "year": 2019,
          "note": "The reflexive 'would this even qualify?' example. Count Rodrigo Prieto, producer Emma Tillinger Koskoff, and Netflix's own hiring, and it clears the bar easily."
        },
        {
          "title": "On the Waterfront",
          "year": 1954,
          "note": "The other reflex; made before the Voting Rights Act, so the retroactive comparison collapses."
        },
        {
          "title": "1917",
          "year": 2019,
          "note": "Amanda's favorite bad-faith objection: the all-white-guy movie the standards supposedly ban, which it doesn't."
        },
        {
          "title": "Moonlight",
          "year": 2016,
          "note": "First of the last four winners Sean runs through, a run of breakthroughs the diversified voting body already produced."
        },
