    {
      "kind": "review",
      "heading": "'Tenet' at the drive-in (spoilers)",
      "note": "recount the movie",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Tenet",
          "year": 2020,
          "note": "Seen at a San Diego drive-in, radio volume in their own hands, which softened the notorious sound mix. For Sean it's the first time Nolan drops the big emotional point and just lets the idea rip: a Bond/Mission: Impossible movie with his time obsession and Ludwig Göransson's score, John David Washington and Robert Pattinson running a two-hour charm Olympics. Also very confusing: he admits to grasping maybe 60-70% of it. Amanda's recap runs from the Kyiv opera raid through the Freeport heist, the inverted highway chase, and the Stalsk-12 temporal pincer, landing on Sator's climate-change motive and the algorithm. A B CinemaScore, Nolan's worst since The Prestige."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "interview",
      "heading": "Antonio Campos on 'The Devil All the Time'",
      "guest": "Antonio Campos on",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "The Devil All the Time",
          "year": 2020,
          "note": "Adapted with his brother from Donald Ray Pollock's novel; a father-son generational story of trauma and faith that blends Southern (Campos says Midwestern) gothic with hard-boiled fiction. He landed Pattinson, Tom Holland, and Sebastian Stan by playing the long game: actors who use their off-franchise time to get weird."
        },
        {
          "title": "Christine",
          "year": 2016,
          "note": "His pre-Sinner feature, and a bigger ensemble than people remember."
        },
        {
          "title": "Afterschool",
          "year": 2008,
          "note": "The Borderline Films debut he still draws a squiggly line from to this movie."
        },
        {
          "title": "Simon Killer",
          "year": 2012,
          "note": "Another single-character study, contrasted with Devil's sprawl."
        },
        {
          "title": "Scarecrow",
          "year": 1973,
          "note": "Jerry Schatzberg's; his last-great-thing, rewatched for the final shot of Hackman smashing a shoe as it cuts to black."
        }
      ]
    }
